The Nasarawa State Commissioner of Health Pharmacist, Ahmed Yahaya on Thursday said that 6 cases of Monkey Pox have been recorded in the state following the outbreak of diseases in the country. The state commissioner who disclosed this while briefing newsmen in his office in Lafia the state capital explained that Monkey Pox is a viral disease caused by the Monkey Pox virus. Pharmacist Ahmed informed that the disease typically lasts for 2-4weeks and is characterised by Fever, headache, muscle pains, shivering, swollen lymph nodes, and a rash that forms blisters and then crusts over. According to the commissioner,” The time from exposure to the disease and onset of symptoms (incubation period) ranges from 5 to 21 days. The disease is severe amongst children, pregnant women and the immuno-suppressed. “The State has recorded Six (6) confirmed Cases of the Disease in the following LGAs; Lafia Four (4) Keffi Two (2) since the outbreak occurred in the Country. He stated that out of 6 cases recovered from the disease from different local governments; adding that no deaths had been recorded so far in the state. He further noted that healthcare workers have been sensitized to the occurrence of this disease, training has been conducted, and drugs and essential commodities for the treatment of the disease have also been procured at General Hospitals, the Dalhatu Araf Specialist Hospital and the Federal Medical Centre, Keffi. The commissioner further said Emergency Operational Centre (EOC) for Monkey Pox has been activated and an Incident Manager has been appointed. -Advertisement- POLL He however informed that the disease can be transmitted through the following means: direct contact with Infectious rash, scabs or body fluids of infected persons, respiratory secretions- face to face prolonged contact, intimate physical contact such as kissing, cuddling or having sex.